<HEADLINE> Defense Rests in Marine Death Case  </HEADLINE>
By RANDALL CHASE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Testimony in the court-martial of a
Marine captain who led a hike that resulted in the heatstroke death
of a reservist ended with defense attorneys questioning the role of
a sergeant who helped lead the hike.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys for Capt. Victor Arana suggested that Sgt.
William Hornsby urged an exhausted Lance Cpl. Giuseppe ''Joey''
Leto to continue the hike and berated other Marines for performing
poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Leto, 21, of New Milford, Conn., died after the July 7 night
march in 80-degree heat at Camp Lejeune. Arana, 28, of Chicago, is
charged with dereliction of duty and failure to obey an order.
</P>
<P>
   The military judge who will decide the case scheduled closing
arguments for this morning after defense attorneys ended their case
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Arana faces a maximum sentence of nine months in prison and
dismissal from the Marines if convicted of both charges.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution witnesses testified that Arana continued to push the
troops despite complaints and questions from other hike
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Arana, who testified Thursday, said he did not realize there
were so many stragglers until the hike was more than half
completed. He said he considered calling in trucks to take the
Marines the rest of the way to their overnight bivouac, but instead
decided to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after the hike, following a head count that prompted a
search for him, Leto was found dead.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Cpl. Ted Casler testified Friday that he heard Leto tell
others he couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard him say, 'I can't make it. I can't go any further,'''
Casler testified. ''Sergeant Hornsby then said, 'Grab my pack,' and
dragged him (piggyback) back to the formation.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hornsby's platoon assembled at the bivouac area, he
berated his men for their performance and ordered them to turn
their shirts inside out, saying they were unworthy to wear Marine
uniforms, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was upset about the hike,'' said Pfc. Jesus Romero. ''A lot
of people fell out. Some sat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornsby testified Arana set a hiking pace that was too fast.
Prosecutors said the hike was to have been conducted at a
2{-miles-an-hour pace, but the company was marched at a
3.7-miles-per-hour rate the first three miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
