<HEADLINE> Campaign Finance Loophole Criticized  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tax-exempt political organizations should be
forced to disclose contributors and expenditures, a bipartisan
group of lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   Without such a requirement, the organizations enjoy one of the
''brashest, boldest loopholes'' in campaign finance law, critics
charged Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is another compelling argument for campaign finance
reform,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. ''Americans should be
outraged at this latest manifestation of corruption in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue are tax-exempt groups organized under Section 527 of
the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   The law is more than 25 years old, but the law has recently been
employed by political organizations of every stripe after court
decisions and an IRS opinion paved the way. A loophole in the law
allows groups organized under Section 527 not to disclose their
contributions or spending.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made campaign finance central to his recent losing
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination. Sen. Russ
Feingold, D-Wis., McCain's partner in the Senate in pushing for
extensive change in campaign finance laws, said activities of
Section 527 organizations amount to ''election advertising dressed
up to avoid the election laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 organizations are involved in political causes and
campaigns across the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a group with Republican ties called Shape the
Debate is running TV ads critical of Vice President Al Gore in
California, New York and Washington. Another called Citizens for
Better Medicare, created by drug manufacturers and their allies,
plans to spend millions of dollars to attack legislation that would
control prescription prices.
</P>
<P>
   The group Common Cause, relying on media accounts, released a
report Friday showing a dozen Section 527 groups, including
Business Leaders for Sensible Priorities, Citizens for Reform,
Saving America's Families Everyday and Republicans for Clean Air,
which stirred the presidential campaign with TV ads praising Texas
Gov. George W. Bush's environmental record and criticizing
then-rival McCain's.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers are pushing bills that would require the
groups to submit financial information to the Federal Election
Commission and detail their existence to the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation faces hurdles. GOP members of the House Ways and
Means Committee voted Thursday against attempts to attach the
measure as an amendment to a tax bill. They argued that it should
await broader campaign finance legislation so as not to drag down
an underlying bill that would expand taxpayer rights and give
people breaks on IRS penalties and interest.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters urged fellow members to pass the measure, which they
hope to get to the House floor next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is high time Congress shines the light on 527s and tells
special-interest groups that the American people are our special
interest,'' said Rep. Dennis Moore, D-Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Common Cause: http://www.commoncause.org
</P>
</TEXT>
