<HEADLINE> Georgia O'Keeffe Works Go on View  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An intimate view of the mature Georgia
O'Keeffe, one of America's great 20th century artists, opens Sunday
at the National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Phillips Collection mounted a major exhibit of
O'Keeffe's canvases. On Sunday the National Gallery brings her back
to Washington with 53 pictures, all on paper -- watercolors,
charcoal drawings and pastels done with a kind of colored chalk.
</P>
<P>
   The show covers only work that she did after a major change in
her style after 1915.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe used up a lot of paper in her long career. She made
hundreds if not thousands of sketches, many if not most of which
have disappeared. Dealers might pay millions now for the early work
that she put out with the trash one night in New York more than 80
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth E. Fine, the gallery's curator of modern drawings, was
impressed with O'Keeffe's lifelong devotion to what she sees as the
intimacy of art on paper.
</P>
<P>
   ''We decided that what we wanted was to show just her finished
work,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In 1915, O'Keeffe mailed some charcoal drawings on paper to a
New York friend to show the kind of work she was doing. Though she
had won an important prize for a realistic painting of a dead
rabbit and a copper pot, she had stopped doing realistic work and
wanted to be rid of her old style.
</P>
<P>
   She had turned to abstract images -- lines and forms that could
not be certainly identified with anything in nature.
</P>
<P>
   The friend took the drawings to photographer Alfred Stieglitz.
O'Keeffe had visited his famous Fifth Avenue art gallery, known
from its address as the ''291,'' but did not know him well. She was
later to become his wife and the model for a famous series of nude
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Abstract art was a hot novelty in 1916 and Stieglitz was
enthusiastic. He put her work into a show at his gallery, and the
college teacher from the South found herself a well-known New York
artist at 29. She had embarked on a new style.
</P>
<P>
   ''I sent for things I had left in Texas,'' she wrote later.
''They came in a barrel and among them were all my old drawings and
paintings. I put them in with the wastepaper trash to throw away
and that night when ... I came home after dark the paintings and
drawings were blowing all over the street. We left them there and
went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Her new abstract work on paper had non-committal titles like
''No. 7 Special'' and ''Early No. 2.'' No one could say with
certainty what they represented -- if anything. O'Keeffe said she
was expressing ''things that I had no words for.''
</P>
<P>
   Stieglitz wrote an article emphasizing what he saw as the
interest of her work from the point of view of psychoanalysis --
Sigmund Freud and his ideas about sex and psychology were also new.
Other critics found O'Keeffe's pictures to be symbols of female
sexuality, even pornographic, despite the lack of realism.
</P>
<P>
   One critic wrote later that she was ''spiritualizing her sex''
and that when women felt strongly it was ''through the womb.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe was impatient with that kind of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''What if it is children and love in paint?'' she asked. ''What
does it matter if the its origin is emotional or aesthetic?''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a cigar is just a cigar, Freud is reported to have
said.
</P>
<P>
   For many years -- she died in 1996 at 98 -- O'Keeffe did both
realistic work and abstractions. But after the criticism, she was
more inclined to relate her abstractions to identifiable objects.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''O'Keeffe on Paper'' will be at the National Gallery of Art
through July 9, and at the Georgia O'Keeffe Museum in Santa Fe, N.
M. July 29-Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Gallery of Art: http://www.nga.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
