<HEADLINE> Closing Arguments in Marine Case  </HEADLINE>
By RANDALL CHASE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine captain charged in the
heatstroke death of a reservist continued to push his troops in a
hike despite repeated warnings that his troops were straggling,
prosecutors said during closing arguments of his court-martial this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Victor Arana violated standard operating procedures for
such conditioning hikes and showed a careless disregard for his
men, Maj. Chris Hamilton told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was like a horse with blinders on...,'' Hamilton said. ''He
was head down, focused forward. There was absolutely no supervision
of that conditioning hike.''
</P>
<P>
   Arana, 28, of Chicago, is charged with dereliction of duty and
failure to obey an order in the death of Lance Cpl. Giuseppe
''Joey'' Leto. Leto, 21, of New Milford, Conn., died of heatstroke
following the July 7 night march in 80-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   Arana faces a maximum sentence of nine months in prison and
dismissal from the Marines if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   His defense attorneys argued this morning that Arana was a
rookie company commander in charge of the unit for only 16 days.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Stevens said Arana did not receive proper instructions from
his superiors and delegated authority to his non-commissioned
officers as allowed in standard operating procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no doubt that there were some judgment and leadership
errors made on this hike,'' Stevens said. ''All judgment errors and
leadership errors do not equate to criminal liability. Good
judgment comes from experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He expected his staff to follow his orders and directions,''
Stevens said. ''His staff failed him that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Arana testified Thursday that he didn't realize there were so
many stragglers until the hike was more than half completed. He
said he considered calling in trucks to take the Marines the rest
of the way, but instead decided to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said in his closing argument that Arana failed to
initiate and maintain radio contact with the officer supervising
the hike. One reason, he said, was that Arana was outpacing his own
radio operator.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the lack of radio contact, Arana could have easily
checked the condition of his troops, Hamilton said, ''All he needed
to do was turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   There were three heat casualties during the second leg of the
hike, not including Leto; all three Marines had body temperatures
higher than 103 degrees, Hamilton. He said Leto was seen vomiting
at the first rest stop.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the hike, Leto wandered more than half a mile from
the area, and Arana failed to obtain a proper head count or weapons
count, Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of this negligent conduct does not meet the standard of
due care that is expected of a company commander to ensure the
safety and welfare of his marines,'' Hamilton told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony in the court-martial ended Friday with defense
attorneys questioning the role of a sergeant who helped lead the
hike.
</P>
<P>
   Arana's attorneys presented testimony suggesting that Sgt.
William Hornsby urged an exhausted Leto to continue the hike and
later berated other Marines for their poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecution witnesses testified that Arana continued to push the
troops despite complaints and questions from other hike
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after the hike, following a head count that prompted a
search for him, Leto was found dead.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Cpl. Ted Casler testified Friday that he heard Leto tell
others he couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard him say, 'I can't make it. I can't go any farther,'''
Casler testified. ''Sergeant Hornsby then said, 'Grab my pack,' and
dragged him (piggyback) back to the formation.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hike, Hornsby berated his men for their performance
and ordered them to turn their shirts inside out, saying they were
unworthy to wear Marine uniforms, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was upset about the hike,'' said Pfc. Jesus Romero. ''A lot
of people fell out. Some sat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornsby testified Arana set a hiking pace that was too fast.
Prosecutors said the hike was to have been conducted at a
2{-miles-an-hour pace, but the company was marched at a
3.7-miles-per-hour rate the first three miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
