<HEADLINE> Rep. Asa Hutchinson Unopposed  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Asa Hutchinson, the Arkansas Republican
who played a prominent role in last year's impeachment trial of
President Clinton, is unopposed for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old Hutchinson never figured to have much of a
struggle winning re-election. He won his second term in 1998 with
80 percent of the vote, and his district chose Republican Bob Dole
over Democrat Bill Clinton in the 1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of a candidate gave Republicans a chance to taunt
Democrats, some of whom had promised to make impeachment managers
sweat for new terms. ''That's the (Democratic) assault on the
managers,'' chided Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., chairman of the House GOP
campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Hutchinson, Rep. Jim DeMint, a freshman from South
Carolina, also has escaped Democratic opposition for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Three lawmakers from Tennessee are without major party
opposition, including Democratic Rep. Harold Ford and Republicans
William Jenkins and John Duncan Jr. Duncan will be opposed by an
independent.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 31 incumbents -- 17 Democrats, 14 Republicans -- are
without major party opposition thus far, with filing closed in
nearly half the states.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Traficant, D-Ohio, has shown affection recently for
House Speaker Dennis Hastert and the Republican majority. Now, they
are returning the favor.
</P>
<P>
   When Traficant wanted a $35 million allocation for a new
community center in Youngstown, Ohio, on a recent housing bill, the
GOP leadership saw to it that his amendment was allowed on the
House floor. And the GOP rank and file helped pass it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to thank the Republican leadership for showing a heart
to my people,'' Traficant said on the House floor at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in favor of his proposal was 225-201. Republicans voted
for it by a margin of 129-87. Democrats opposed it, 112-96.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant, a lifelong Democrat, has made numerous comments
recently that he might decide to back Hastert for speaker next year
over the Democratic leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   With the House narrowly divided, the importance of a potential
switch like Traficant's is magnified.
</P>
<P>
   And the political subtext was unmistakable during debate on the
$35 million.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant noted that the amendment provided money for ''this
significant project that Speaker Hastert has identified as a
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., responded: ''I do not deny that this
whole process speaks to the need of the speaker. I have a pretty
good idea of exactly what that need is in the current political
context.''
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, Traficant delivered something of a lecture
on Democratic affinity for public works projects, including one in
Massachusetts that former Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill shepherded to
passage more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now when you built that tunnel up there in Boston and Tip
O'Neill built that tunnel, I did not open my mouth,'' he said in
reference to a project now known as the ''Big Dig.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When that great Tombigbee was built, everybody stepped
aside,'' he added, referring to a multibillion dollar waterway
project in the South that the Democratic leadership also supported.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   It's become customary in recent years for the Senate to whistle
through numerous nonbinding amendments in moments before final
passage of a budget.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Senate Budget Committee chairman, Republican Pete
Domenici of New Mexico, sought approval without votes for a package
of 55 such proposals on Friday -- on issues ranging from flood
control to breast cancer -- Sen. Robert C. Byrd objected.
</P>
<P>
   In strong language, the West Virginia Democrat said he did not
want to participate in the ''gang rape of the legislative
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd suggested the Senate stay in session as long as necessary
to debate and vote on the proposals. But cooler heads -- and the
desire for a Friday afternoon getaway from the Capitol -- prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   The budget passed moments later, without any action on the
nonbinding proposals and without any formal protest from the
numerous senators who had sponsored them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
