<HEADLINE> Seaman Accused in Gov't Memo Theft  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A civilian Defense Department employee who worked
aboard an ammunition supply ship has been charged with theft of
sensitive government documents.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Steven Smith, 37, was arrested without incident Friday
in San Diego by FBI and Naval Criminal Investigative Service
agents. He remained jailed Saturday pending a court appearance next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was assigned as a seaman aboard the USNS Kilauea, part of
the Military Sealift Command, an FBI news release said. The command
is based in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Times quoted an unidentified Justice Department
source as saying the complaint alleged Smith possessed information
about unspecified ammunition aboard the ship and was considering
putting the information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Special Agent John Iannarelli said the theft occurred April
1, when the ship was moored at Naval Station Bremerton on the Puget
Sound. The charges were filed in a federal court in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is charged with obtaining documents respecting national
security, the FBI said. He is also charged with theft of government
property including documents and computer disks.
</P>
</TEXT>
